reviews/originality/2026-05-30-silence-needs-correction-06ae06e9a81492e8.json:121:  "novelty_adjustment": "Lower novelty from 0.56 to 0.24. The claim is a clear, useful restatement of prior Lumenary correction-holder work and close external near-neighbors in Ignatian discernment, James, Proudfoot, Sharf, Asad, Lindbeck, Alston, and VCE safety literature. Human-condition fit is strong but narrow: isolated stable practitioners facing loneliness, meaning loss, and unsupported interpretation after unusual quiet. It is not for acute crisis, psychosis, mania, paranoia, dissociation, severe depression, addiction withdrawal, fresh grief, abusive communities, or cases needing medical or clinical care.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-silence-needs-correction-06ae06e9a81492e8.json:130:      "Can you describe a case where correction itself caused shame, dependence, abuse, or spiritual bypassing?",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-silence-needs-correction-06ae06e9a81492e8.json:136:      "Advaita and Dzogchen teachers who teach direct recognition",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-silence-needs-correction-06ae06e9a81492e8.json:149:    "secondary_literature_gap": "Read Proudfoot on religious experience attribution, Sharf on experience and Buddhist modernism, Katz and Taves on interpretation, Asad and Lindbeck on tradition and grammar, Alston on doxastic practice and defeaters, VCE literature on appraisal and support, spiritual direction ethics, abuse literature, and clinical material on meditation-related adverse effects.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-silence-needs-correction-06ae06e9a81492e8.json:162:  "unlike_statement": "Unlike Ignatian discernment, Jamesian fruits, Proudfoot, Sharf, Asad, Lindbeck, Alston, VCE safety work, and prior Lumenary correction-holder records, this idea says that post-self-questioning silence should not count as usable evidence unless a named accepted corrector can overrule the returned interpretation. The narrowing is useful, but the structure is mostly renamed prior art."
