reviews/originality/2026-05-30-no-one-begins-alone-3260ddf016476c06.md:128:- Close-read SN 22.59, SN 45.2, Shinran letters or Tannisho, Bendowa, Huangbo, and one Dzogchen or Mahamudra source before public wording.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-prescriptive-custody-of-beginnings.md:29:The candidate may still compress a messy causal ecology into one elegant frame. Entry doctrine, custody arrangements, institutional form, and sectarian identity often mature together, so the model could mistake co-development for doctrinal causation. Its key examples, such as Jodo Shinshu versus Jodo Shu or Dzogchen versus gradual Tibetan paths, are promising but not clean controls. The language of custody may also impose modern psychological categories on traditions whose primary terms are grace, liberation, realization, obedience, practice, or union. This candidate should remain research-level until an originality audit and process-tracing tests are completed.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-prescriptive-custody-of-beginnings.md:57:- Use matched comparisons, especially Jodo Shinshu versus Jodo Shu, Dzogchen versus gradual Tibetan sutra-path practice, and explicit grace traditions versus neighboring cooperation traditions.
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes-0e142612673940d0.json:4:    "anomaly_candidate": "Pure Land nembutsu and Dogen practice-realization.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-30-stop-when-the-repair-changes-0e142612673940d0.json:6:    "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "These may not be best understood as tools that repair a named modern wound. Nembutsu can function as entrusting gratitude under Other Power, and Dogen can refuse a separable tool-result model. Forcing them through a repair-survival gate may distort the native practice before it protects the borrower."
